The company should be a real B2B ingredient, extract, flavor/fragrance, natural preservation, or botanical antioxidant company. The product or solution should be a source-presented product, grade, SKU, solution line, branded offering, or product family tied to rosemary extract, rosemary-derived antioxidant compounds, or a rosemary-containing natural antioxidant blend. The cited page must show a commercial ingredient / B2B ingredient context; consumer supplement, retail wellness, broad ingredient-definition, and generic ecommerce product pages do not pass merely because they mention rosemary extract or antioxidant health language.

Evidence axes:
- `official_product_identity`: a supplier/company-controlled product page, public catalog, public brochure, TDS/PDS, or comparable official surface naming the product or solution locally on the page and tying that named product to rosemary extract, rosemary-derived antioxidant compounds, or a rosemary-containing botanical antioxidant blend with antioxidant, natural preservation, shelf-life, oxidation-control, rancidity, color, flavor, or comparable protection function. Third-party marketplace, distributor, trade, and mirrored-collateral pages fail this axis even when they quote supplier text.
- `source_stated_role_or_operation`: a public source explicitly stating what the company does for the named product or solution family in its own or the source's words, such as grows, extracts, standardizes, blends, manufactures, supplies, distributes, or provides that named ingredient solution. Do not assign roles that the source does not state; "offers", "available from", "brand page", "product page", or generic company capability wording is not enough to infer manufacturer, extractor, supplier, distributor, or vertically integrated status. An official product page can pass only when the role or operation wording is explicit and local to the named product or solution family.
- `application_or_segment_claim`: a public source stating a product-local application, product category, or customer segment such as food, meat, oils/fats, pet food, supplements, cosmetics, flavor/fragrance, or another clearly named segment. Preserve wording; do not turn it into a use recommendation. Marketplace taxonomy tags, broad catalog section headings, generic antioxidant/category pages, and page navigation labels do not pass unless the application wording is directly attached to the named product or solution in source-controlled technical or commercial context.
- `external_presence`: independent third-party validation such as a distributor item page, trade-show/exhibitor profile, ingredient-network article/profile, reputable food/ingredient trade article, or comparable source that specifically ties the company-product to rosemary extract, rosemary-derived antioxidants, or a rosemary-containing natural antioxidant ingredient space. The third-party source must name both the company and the product or stable item and add independent context such as seller/distributor relationship, manufacturer identity, exhibitor/product profile, or editorial coverage. A self-serve marketplace storefront, vendor store product card, sample/quote card, broad category/listing/search page, or supplier-uploaded marketplace profile does not pass merely because it is on a third-party domain.

Certification, regulatory, labeling, food-safety, geography, and date wording are useful only when the source states them. Source silence should be handled as missing or unclear evidence, not as inferred absence or adequacy.

The task is public provenance only: no market sizing, supplier ranking, procurement recommendation, formulation or dosage guidance, compliance conclusion, food-safety assurance, customer targeting, outreach, lead scoring, contact enrichment, or inferred value-chain classification.

